Systemic treatment with AT-RvD1 diminishes the progression of the disease in salivary epithelium from female mice as follows: reduces pro-inflammatory molecule gene expression
AT-RvD1 enhances the resolution of airway inflammation.
AT-RvD1 can serve as important modulator of allergic airway responses by decreasing eosinophils and pro-inflammatory mediators and promoting macrophage clearance of allergen.

Treatment of VSMC with AT-RvD1 inhibits PDGF-stimulated Rac1 activity.
Treatment of VSMC with AT-RvD1 attenuates paxillin localization to focal adhesions.
VASP is another crucial regulator of actin polymerization, which down-regulates actin filament formation in its phosphorylated form.

VSMC migration is a complex process involving an orchestrated concert of molecular events leading to actin polymerization. Rac1 is a crucial regulator of actin filament formation, and its activity is required to promote VSMC migration.
The subsequent activation of PKA interferes with with focal adhesion formation by decreasing paxillin localization to the cell leading edge.

AT-RvD1 interferes with the PDGF pathway by attenuating paxillin localization at the leading edge of migrating VSMCs, suggesting decreased focal adhesion formation as an important mechanism by which AT-RvD1 can regulate VSMC migration. Although AT-RvD1 effects on paxillin appeared PKA-dependent, the intermediate effectors between PKA and paxillin remain to be explored.

VSMC migration is a complex process involving an orchestrated concert of molecular events leading to actin polymerization. Actin polymerization dynamics are central to the cytoskeletal rearrangements that take place during VSMC leading edge formation and migration. Rac1 is a crucial regulator of actin filament formation, and its activity is required to promote VSMC migration.
The expression of CXCL1, a chemokine that plays a key role in neutrophil recruitment, was reduced by 27-fold in the AT-RvD1-treated group compared with control mice.
AT-RvD1 decreases IL-12 expression, which could be one of the reasons for reduced Th1 cell activity, as sustained IL-12 signaling is required for Th1 polarization
AT-RvD1 treatment resulted in reduced corneal neovascularization, likely because of inhibitory effects on the production of VEGF-A which is involved in pathologic angiogenesis.
AT-RvD1 attenuates STAT1, which plays an important role in Th1 cell differentiation and IFN-γ expression.
The mechanisms by which AT-RvD1 acts appear to be multiple. These include inhibitory effects on matrix metalloproteinase 9 (MMP-9).
The effects of AT-RvD1 on VSMC migration and PKA activity are attenuated by blocking ALX/FPR2, suggesting an important role of this G-protein coupled receptor.

First, we monitored phagocytosis of live fluorescence-labeled E. coli by bone marrow-derived macrophages (BMDM) using real-time imaging. Fluorescence intensity increased with time (0-120 min) represents increased macrophage ingestion of E. coli. RvD2 addition prior to E. coli (10 nM, 15 min) significantly enhanced phagocytosis (~95% at 100 min). This RvD2 action was not observed in DRV2-KO BMDM, indicating the role of the RvD2-DRV2 axis in stimulating bacterial clearance via phagocytosis. Since cyclic AMP activates PKA, which can phosphorylate pCREB, we determined cyclic AMP levels with naïve peritoneal resident macrophages and found that RvD2 (10 - 100 nM) significantly increased cyclic AMP levels in WT but not DRV2-KO. A sub-optimal concentration of Forskolin (10 μM) was used as a control and taken as 100%. This is consistent with earlier findings that RvD2 (10-100 nM) increases cyclic AMP levels that are dependent on DRV2 in human macrophages.

RvD2 time-dependently increased phosphorylation of pAKT, pp38MAPK, pCREB, pS6, pERK1/2, pSTAT1, pSTAT3 and pSTAT5 each with different kinetics in macrophages. pAKT, pp38MAPK, pCREB, pS6 levels reached maximum at 1 min then gradually declined. pERK1/2 was detected at 1 min and peaked at 30 min after RvD2 stimulation. In comparison, pSTAT1, pSTAT3 and pSTAT5 were also markedly increased as early as 1 min, and their levels remained elevated till 15-30 min. In macrophages from DRV2-KO, up-regulation of these phospho-proteins by RvD2 was abolished. [...] These results indicate that RvD2 regulates phosphorylation of select kinases and transcription factors with different kinetics in macrophages in a DRV2-dependent manner.

STAT3 and PKA inhibition, but not ERK inhibition significantly blocked RvD2-stimulated phagocytosis. Together, our results demonstrate that DRV2 contributes to RvD2’s pro-resolving actions in macrophage clearance of live E. coli and this action is dependent on cyclic AMP-PKA and STAT3 signaling pathways.

Local administration of RvD3 significantly reduced neutrophil transmigration in response to TNF-α-initiated acute inflammation (~65% reduction). Assessment of inflammatory exudate cytokine and chemokine levels demonstrated a significant reduction in MCP-1 (~70%), IL-6 (~90%) and KC (~50%). Similarly, AT-RvD3 potently reduced PMN recruitment into the pouch (~75%), while also reducing exudate pro-inflammatory cytokine and chemokine levels. Together these results demonstrate the potent local and systemic anti-inflammatory actions of RvD3 and AT-RvD3 counter-regulating local pro-inflammatory mediator production and dampening leukocyte recruitment.

Using multiple reaction monitoring (MRM), we quantified individual mediator levels and found that systemically delivered RvD3 significantly reduced LTB4 (~80%), PGD2 (~67%) and TxB2 (~50%) while stimulating the production of PGE2. AT-RvD3 reduced local LTB4, PGD2 and TxB2 levels while increasing PGE2. Together these results demonstrate that both synthetic RvD3 and AT-RvD3 possess potent anti-inflammatory actions regulating local eicosanoid levels, characteristic of specialized pro-resolving mediators.

Zymosan administration via i.p. injection gave rapid PMN infiltration into the peritoneal cavity at 4 hr. Shown on the representative dot plots and bar graphs, RvD4 at 10 ng/mouse decreased percent of PMN, giving ~31% reduction at 4 hours. For comparison, administration of an equal amount of the potent immunoresolvent RvD3 also gave ~44% reduction in PMN infiltration. With the biological activity of RvD4 confirmed, we next assessed its in vivo actions in S. aureus-mediated infection probing its action as well as temporal formation. To determine its role in bacterial killing and host protection during S. aureus infections, RvD4 was administered at 200 ng/mouse concomitantly with a self-limited bacterial inoculation (105 c.f.u) into the dorsal pouch of male FVB mice. Resolution indices were then measured. RvD4 potently reduced neutrophilic infiltration by ~40% at Tmax (12 h) and shortened the resolution interval in mice treated with RvD4 from 6 to 3 hr.

RvD4 (0.01 nM to 10 nM) promoted bacterial phagocytosis by human macrophages (12–18%) to a similar extent as the pro-resolving mediator RvD3. RvD4 also promoted the phagocytosis of opsonized zymosan A at concentrations as low as 0.1–10 nM, significantly enhancing macrophage uptake by 40–60% above vehicle controls.

RvD4 statistically significantly increased macrophage efferocytosis of apoptotic neutrophils by 40–50% at concentrations as low as 0.1–10 nM. These results suggest that RvD4 enhances human macrophage functions in clearing cellular debris and microbial particles. Together these results provide evidence that RvD4 is pro-resolving with human phagocytes.

Given that RvD4 displayed potent pro-resolving actions in skin infection, we investigated whether it also acts on human dermal fibroblasts. RvD4 potently promoted the clearance of apoptotic PMN by human fibroblasts by ~59% at 1 nM. Of the SPM tested, RvD4 and RvD1 at 1 nM gave the highest increase in apoptotic cell uptake (~52 and 57%).

Given that RvD4 displayed potent pro-resolving actions in skin infection, we investigated whether it also acts on human dermal fibroblasts. RvD4 potently promoted the clearance of apoptotic PMN by human fibroblasts by ~59% at 1 nM. Of the SPM tested, RvD4 and RvD1 at 1 nM gave the highest increase in apoptotic cell uptake (~52 and 57%).

For these experiments, PMNs were exposed to either RvD1 or AT-RvD1 (0–1000 nm) to assess their impact with fMLP-stimulated (100 nm) transendothelial migration. [B]oth RvD1 and AT-RvD1 stopped PMN transmigration in a concentration-dependent fashion. Although both molecules potently reduced PMN transmigration by as much as 65 ± 8% at 1 μm concentrations of AT-RvD1 (EC50 ∼ 30 nm), no statistically significant differences were noted between RvD1 or its aspirin-triggered form AT-RvD1 at the concentrations tested. A reduction in PMN transmigration of ∼50% was obtained with concentrations as low as 10 nm.

Both RvD1 and AT-RvD1 limited total leukocytic infiltration at each dose tested with the maximal decrease in total leukocytes with as little as a 100 ng dose per mouse. At the 10-ng dose, AT-RvD1 reduced leukocytic infiltration to a greater extent than RvD1 (∼23% and ∼8–10%). Both RvD1 and AT-RvD1 exhibited a dose-dependent reduction in PMN infiltration (Fig. 6B) with similar potency and efficacy (maximal inhibition of ∼35% at dose of 100 ng/mouse). Furthermore, both compounds were bioactive at the lowest dose administered (1 ng/mouse), demonstrating the very potent actions of these mediators.

8-oxo-RvD1 (10 ng/mouse) limited PMN infiltration in murine peritonitis by a statistically significant 41%, which was comparable to RvD1 (44%). In sharp contrast, 17-oxo-RvD1 did not decrease PMN infiltration in vivo in a statistically significant manner. When compared with the actions of RvD1, 8-oxo-RvD1 was as effective (∼93% the activity of RvD1), whereas 17-oxo-RvD1 was significantly less bioactive (∼10%).

RvD5 given in physiologic range, i.e. nanograms/mouse with E. coli (107 CFU) significantly enhanced phagocyte containment of E. coli in vivo (160% increase) compared to mice challenged with E. coli alone. RvD1 shared this action, registering 42% increase. Of note, RvD1 or RvD5 markedly reduced blood and exudate bacterial counts. Infected mice developed hypothermia, giving 2.4±1.2°C decrements in body (surface) temperature. Both RvD1 and RvD5 prevented this. The higher lethal dose E. coli (2.5×10^7 CFU) gave only 25% survival and RvD1 significantly increased survival to ~66%. Here, RvD5 significantly reduced pro-inflammatory cytokines KC and TNFα in exudates and RvD1 decreased IL-1β. Thus, both RvD1 and RvD5 stimulated phagocyte E. coli ingestion, lowered bacterial titers, protected from hypothermia and increased survival.

Zymosan A, a glucan from a yeast cell wall, was used to induce sterile peritonitis characterized by acute PMN infiltration. Administration of 10 ng/mouse of the 17,18-diHEPE isomers (compounds V (18S) and VI (18R)) significantly blocked PMN infiltration by 27.9 ± 8.2 and 43.7% ± 1.3%, respectively. In contrast, little effect was observed by the administration of 11,18-diHEPEs (compounds I–IV), which show the structure-specific activity of 17,18-diHEPEs. Compound V at 100 ng/mouse and compound VI at 10 ng/mouse dramatically inhibited PMN infiltration and were almost as potent as higher doses of RvE2 (1 μg/mouse) or dexamethasone (10 μg/mouse).
